  "issue_number": 108,
  "issue_title": "feature: add find_element tool",
  "issue_body": "## Problem\n\nCurrent tool calls need reliable target resolution, but agents often need to inspect whether a specific element exists before choosing an action. Reusing raw observe output for this makes routing brittle and pushes too much parsing into the reasoning layer.\n\n## Proposed behavior\n\nAdd a `find_element` Android tool that searches the current screen context and returns structured candidate nodes.\n\nExpected arguments:\n\n- `text`: optional visible text query.\n- `content_description`: optional accessibility description query.\n- `node_id`: optional stable node identifier.\n- `class_name`: optional Android class filter.\n- `match`: optional match mode such as `exact`, `contains`, or `semantic` when supported.\n- `limit`: optional maximum candidates.\n\n## User workflow\n\nThe agent can call `find_element({text=Settings})`, inspect the returned candidates, then call a target-aware action such as `tap` or future bounds-based action with the selected target.\n\n## Local-first impact\n\nThis gives the local router and small model a structured lookup primitive instead of forcing them to parse full UI trees.\n\n## Safety and security considerations\n\nResults must preserve existing sensitive-text redaction and sensitivity flags. The tool should not return hidden/private fields beyond the existing accessibility observation boundary.\n\n## Acceptance criteria\n\n- Tool is registered in the Android tool catalog.\n- Returns structured candidates with stable id, display-safe text, content description, class, bounds, enabled/clickable flags, and sensitivity marker when available.\n- Supports bounded candidate limits.\n- Includes tests for matching modes and sensitive-text redaction.\n- Live-test checklist covers exact text, partial text, content description, and no-match cases.",
  "merged_at": "2026-05-28T13:22:20.000Z",
